{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1781755281,"nonce":"1r3ZzuqQKyz+aeJpeGgxTFkCpVs=","message":"PR1 (aggregate expressions) is up as PR #31 on branch feature/aggregate-expressions: COUNT/SUM/AVG/MIN/MAX builders with nullable+widening result typing, dialect-aware casts, and aggregates over nullable/left-joined columns. The full SUM/AVG operand-type x backend decode matrix is exhaustively tested.\n\nTwo known limitations deferred to the GROUP BY / HAVING work (the next slice of this bug), since both need query-position / context tracking:\n\n- Nested aggregates (e.g. col.sum().sum()) type-check but render SUM(SUM(...)), which the database rejects.\n- An aggregate used in where_ (e.g. u.id.sum().greater_than(5)) compiles but is invalid SQL; it needs HAVING.\n\nPreventing these at the type level belongs with GROUP BY/HAVING, which is the natural next PR.","files":null}]}